The UK Second-Generation Search and Rescue (UKSAR2G) programme will procure a successor service to both the UK Search and Rescue - Helicopters (UKSARH) and Aerial Surveillance and Verification (ASV) contracts when they expire between 2024 and 2026.

These contracts provide Her Majesty&apos;s Coastguard with helicopter assets and operations to comply with international Search and Rescue (SAR) obligations, rescuing people in distress around the UK coast, and fixed-wing assets and operations to monitor polluting, illegal or anti-competitive activity. MCA has developed proposals for a successor service which:

1. moves away from the existing &apos;one-size-fits-all&apos; approach, with market-led asset data;

2. recognises the collaborative nature of SAR and how it is utilised by other government agencies;

3. encourages maximum competition to drive value and innovation, for example use of unmanned (drone) assets during the lifetime of the contract; and

4. continues to provide a service that rescues thousands of people every year.

The contract has been awarded to Brent Centre for Young People (BCYP) following market engagement to invite capable providers. Brent Centre for Young People (BCYP) has been established as the only capable provider.

The BCYP Service is available to young people aged between 14-21 who are resident in the borough of Brent or are registered with a Brent GP.

The objectives of the Service are to:
• Improve mental health and emotional well- being of young people;
• Improve relationships with family;
• Increase young people's knowledge and understanding in relation to mental health and
emotional well-being;
• Promote and encourage a positive attitude towards a healthy lifestyle;
• Encourage young people to reduce or become abstinent from drug use;
• Reduce un-safe sexual behaviour. Reduce offending and re-offending; and
• Encourage young people to re-enter the education system or complete education/skills training course(s).

Leeds City Council is seeking to procure a cloud hosted Highways and Transportation Digital Information Management System to:  • support asset management;  • manage the highway network considering customer needs, local priorities, asset condition; and  • make the best use of resources to deliver the most effective highway maintenance services. 
The key requirements are that any proposed system must:
•	Be cloud hosted;
•	Maintain a Register of Assets with comprehensive and flexible records retention, archiving and deletion functionality;
•	Facilitate the scheduling, coordination and cost management of inspections and maintenance works, as well as raising works orders;
•	Assist with forward planning and prioritisation;
•	Support the management of the highway network and coordination of road closures, planned works, permits, and licenses;
•	Have mapping functionality to plot the location of assets, plan routes and display other spatial data sets;
•	Utilise mobile technology to allow for data collection in the field;
•	Include a reporting tool comprising a comprehensive suite of reports as well as the ability to create user defined reports;
•	Interface with other Leeds City Council systems; as well as external systems such as DfT Street Manager and BIM360;
•	Meet GDPR and PSN compliance requirements.
The following Software and Services, as a minimum, shall be provided under this contract:
•	Highways and Transportation Digital Information Management System (cloud hosted)
•	Any additional modules/functionality required to meet LCC requirements
•	Implementation services
•	Installation services
•	Configuration services
•	Integration services
•	Migration services
•	On-going support and maintenance services
•	System development and customisation
•	Training
•	Software/system upgrades

The objectives of the project are:
To evaluate and understand the main drivers of a positive reputation for a low-tariff university.
To understand how the University is viewed by different audiences, and to be given the tools in order for us to improve these perceptions where possible. 
o propose an action plan which will:
•	Evaluate and measure the University's current reputational strengths and weaknesses;
•	Identify audiences and actions where it would be most prudent to look to improve the University's reputation (either through the improvement of views among audiences with the most negative views of the institution, or towards audiences or actions which might yield the greatest return on resource investment);
•	Establish measures which could be used in order to track shifts in the University's reputation at a later date;
•	Establish a framework though which continuous improvement can be signposted, realised and measured through marketing and communicating University activity.
